Bayern are fully prepared for an 'arrogant' Mourinho
By Christopher Davies in Wolfsburg
12:01AM BST 04 Apr 2005
Comments
Germany's national newspaper, Bild, did not mince its words. "And you thought Bayern were arrogant? Meet Chelsea's manager-lout" was the headline while underneath were some of Jose Mourinho's more outrageous quotes, with spin that ensured the Portuguese looked even more of an egotist than he is. The latest episode in 'Josegate', the seemingly never-ending saga of Mourinho versus UEFA, is that Mourinho is apparently so unhappy with the lack of loyalty shown by Chelsea and chairman Bruce Buck at not fighting his two-game suspension he is threatening to quit at the end of the season - an unusual way, if true, of showing loyalty to the club. The story, initially in the Portuguese press, soon made its way round Europe and was devoured with relish in Germany, the media stoking the verbal fire as Bayern Munich prepared for Wednesday's visit to Stamford Bridge with a stroll in the sun, beating VfL Wolfsburg 3-0. Mourinho does not talk to the English media these days but enjoys a closer relationship with the Portuguese press so it would be unusual for them to fabricate such a story without a well-placed leak. Bayern coach Felix Magath was intrigued. "If it is true he could leave, it could cause a lot of problems, a lot of trouble at the club," he said after the victory in Wolfsburg.
Related Articles
Hargreaves and Bayern in bullish mood
03 Apr 2005
Mourinho sent chief scout Andre Villas Boas, unsurprisingly banned from speaking to the press, to the Volkswagen Arena to run the rule over Bayern, who maintained their position at the top of the Bundesliga in a canter. First-half goals by Bastian Schweinsteiger - a right-foot volley from Torsten Frings' centre - and an unfortunate own goal by Kevin Hofland enabled the visitors to, in the words of Frings, "step down a gear, which helped us prepare for Chelsea". Frings got the slightest of touches to Schweinsteiger's left-wing cross to head Bayern's third in a game that became little more than a glorified training session for the superior Bavarians. Left-back Bixente Lizarazu said: "I think it is not always so easy to win like this here in Wolfsburg so we are very happy about the result. This was a perfect preparation for Chelsea. It will be a very interesting contest between two very good teams in Europe. "I would say that the style of the two teams is a little bit the same so it will be interesting to see what happens. "Chelsea have very good organisation, a very strong defence, and we know they play 'controlling' football. They have very quick players so are always a team that is very difficult to play. But we are a little bit the same, you know. We are playing the same way..." Lizarazu was wary of becoming involved in Chelsea's internal politics. "It has been difficult for them, but this is not really our problem," he said. "We don't care about that. We are playing a game against one of the best teams in Europe. "I don't know how it will affect the team for the coach not to be in the dressing room. I was never in such a situation so I do not know. You have to speak to the players of Chelsea but for us it does not matter." Bayern will be without Claudio Pizarro (hamstring). Sebastian Deisler or Mehmet Scholl will probably replace the promising Schweinsteiger in midfield or Magath may play both in a 4-5-1 formation with Roy Makaay a lone striker. Makaay came off in the 56th minute and did not take part in yesterday's training because of problems with a thigh muscle but the Holland striker is optimistic he will be fit to face Chelsea. "I hope so," said Magath. "A complete loss of our attack would be quite problematic." Football
