Hull City defender Paul McShane tastes glory of promotion after suffering pain and rejection One moment Paul McShane was nudging in the goal that seemingly would send Hull City back to the Premier League. Half an hour later, McShane crouched in the tunnel with his team-mates, considering the possibility of an immediate future in the Championship play-offs. Goal crazy: Paul McShane (centre) after scoring the decisive goal Photo: REUTERS	By Si Hughes, KC Stadium
11:00PM BST 05 May 2013
Comments
Then Leeds United scored at Watford in the delayed game and Hull were up. McShane’s goal — even though it was not a winner — proved to be decisive. One moment Paul McShane was nudging in the goal that seemingly would send Hull City back to the Premier League . Half an hour later, McShane crouched in the tunnel with his team-mates, considering the possibility of an immediate future in the Championship play-offs. Then Leeds United scored at Watford in the delayed game and Hull were up. McShane’s goal — even though it was not a winner — proved to be decisive. At the moment of reckoning, the defender thought about both the glory and the pain. High in the stands there were the proud, smiling faces of more than a dozen family and friends. Absent, though, was his father, Sean, a former Dublin hurler, who died suddenly in 2010 aged 65 from a blood clot after routine ankle surgery. There was the private torment associated with suffering such a loss, but solace could not be found in a professional career. Two months after his father’s death, McShane was relegated from the Premier League with Hull. Later, with the arrival of Nigel Pearson as manager, and Nick Barmby after him, there seemed to be no future for the defender on Humberside. In the 2011-12 season, he made just one appearance. Reluctantly, he agreed loan moves to Barnsley and Crystal Palace. Related Articles
