In his darkest hours, despite only being in his mid-20s, he considered quitting football. In one of the few quiet corners of the KC Stadium on Saturday afternoon, McShane still in his full muddied kit, shin pads and boots, recalled his story with a man of the match award in one hand and a bottle of beer in the other. “You train every day at your hardest and you’re not even considered, which is very frustrating,” he said. “Some people at the club wouldn’t talk to me at one stage because I was deemed as a bad egg or something because I wasn’t playing. “I was really contemplating it, just getting in my car, getting on the boat and going back to Ireland because it was just wall after wall that I kept hitting. But I kept going and that’s what you’ve got to keep doing, for yourself more than anything. I was giving my all so I could hold my head up.” With the appointment of Steve Bruce as manager last summer, McShane’s fortunes changed. In suffering rejection, the pair had something in common. Bruce was still smarting from his sacking at Sunderland. Talks were scheduled between Bruce and all squad members. “We had a remarkable conversation where Paul said he’d never trusted any manager he had worked under,” Bruce said. “I asked him to give me a chance because he had something to offer for certain. He never gave up and has a big heart. He’s had some stick and a difficult couple of years. But he’ll be the first one I speak to in the next couple of weeks and offer a new contract.”
McShane helped Hull to promotion by starting many games on the left side of a back three. Against Cardiff, Bruce switched the formation with McShane as a left-back and Robbie Brady, the player who usually fills that position, operating admirably as an emergency centre-forward. Bruce probably knows this current squad would not be strong enough to succeed in a Premier League survival mission. “You have to win 10 games. That sounds easy, but it’s not,” Bruce said. “If we think we’ll be signing people for £15 million, then we are far mistaken. If you’re trying to get a player like that, then he will have five or six clubs to choose from. You bring them here and burn huge money. I won’t do that to the chairman. “If you get people on big contracts, then you’re lumbering your club. There won’t be anything silly. Otherwise, it would be a Portsmouth.”
“We can do a Wigan Athletic or a West Bromwich Albion, building the club and making it stronger and put it in a healthy situation. To do that you need trust, and I know the trust of the owner is there.” That owner, Assem Allam, an Egyptian-born industrialist, bought Hull two years ago when the club was four days from bankruptcy. He described achieving promotion as one of “the proudest” moments in his life. Match details Hull City (4-4-2): Stockdale, Chester, McShane, Faye, Elmohamady, Boyd, Meyler, Quinn, Rosenior, Simpson (Proschwitz 45), Brady (Fathi 88).
Subs: Jakupovic, Hobbs, Evans, Fryatt, Bruce.
Booked: Elmohamady, Proschwitz.
Cardiff (4-4-2): Marshall, McNaughton, Turner, Nugent, Taylor, Noone (Maynard 84), Gunnarsson, Kim (Gestede 64), Conway,Velikonja (Campbell 46), Mutch.
Subs: Lewis, Whittingham, Smith, Lappin.
Sent off: Taylor. Booked Taylor, Nugent, Gunnarsson. Referee: K Stroud (Hampshire).
Five things Hull need to do
By Arindam Rej
1. Buy a striker
Hull’s attacking football has often been blunted by their own final-third failings, with Nick Proschwitz having struggled to adapt and Jay Simpson being a workhorse provider but not a finisher.
2. Keep the manager
Steve Bruce has departed quickly from clubs before and his stock is rising again. Even if Hull struggle, he is still the highest-calibre boss they could realistically hope for.
3. Maintain tactical versatility
Bruce has sprung surprises with his team selections and tactics, including the shock decision to ditch their wing-backs system against Cardiff, and must keep being instinctive even against the bigger clubs.
4. Make loans permanent
Hull’s most dangerous player this season, winger Ahmed Elmohamady, needs to stay put, while the likes of goalkeeper David Stockdale and midfielder George Boyd, practically a done deal, need to be tied up.
5. Be financially prudent
The long term must be considered to avoid any financial difficulties should they go down again with no repeat of contracts such as the £45,000-a-week, five-year one given to Jimmy Bullard five years ago.
